
Website Realization and Page Composition Standard
Level 2 Artifact

Version 1.0  |  Baseline
Status
Governing artifact — active realization authority.


1.  Purpose, Scope, Role, and Relationship
1.1  Purpose
This document defines the realization standard for website solutions governed under the Website Solution System Framework.

Its purpose is to define:
•	the buildable modules used to realize the website solution
•	the reusable components used across those modules
•	the governed page model used to manage and construct pages
•	the rules by which modules and components are composed into pages
•	the CMS-managed versus fixed aspects of realization
•	the conformance rules that ensure realized pages and modules remain within the governed structural system
1.2  Scope
This document is in scope for:
•	buildable module definition and classification
•	reusable component definition and usage rules
•	the distinction between page type, page instance, and page composition
•	module integration contracts
•	page construction rules
•	page-level orchestration and ownership
•	CMS-managed versus fixed realization concerns
•	conformance rules for realization and page composition
1.3  Out of Scope
This document is not the place where:
•	product requirements for a specific website are defined
•	the structural architecture of the website solution is defined
•	current site-specific configuration values are defined
•	stack-specific technical implementation choices are defined

Those belong to the Website Specification, Website Solution Architecture Standard, Site Configuration artifacts, and Technical Build Profile respectively.
1.4  Role
This document is the Level 2 realization and composition artifact for the website solution system.

It defines the governed buildable system that realizes the structural architecture and the governed way in which pages are composed and managed.
1.5  Governing Relationship
This document derives from:
•	Website Solution System Framework
•	Website Specification
•	Site Configuration Standard
•	Site Configuration Record
•	Website Solution Architecture Standard

This document constrains:
•	Technical Build Profile
•	site-specific page and module realization decisions
•	developer implementation decisions
•	code-generation outputs related to modules, components, page composition, and CMS-managed variation
1.6  Authority
This document is authoritative within its declared scope for the buildable realization system, reusable component usage, page model, and page composition rules.

It must not override upstream artifacts within their scope and must not be silently overridden by downstream artifacts.
2.  Governing Principles
2.1  Realization Must Conform to Architecture
All buildable modules, reusable components, page models, and page composition rules must conform to the Website Solution Architecture Standard.
2.2  Module Versus Component Distinction
Buildable modules and reusable components are distinct constructs and must not be conflated.
2.3  Page Composition Is Governed
Pages must be composed through governed page rules and composition logic, not through local improvisation.
2.4  Page Composition Is Centrally Owned
Page construction is owned by the governed page composition model, not by individual modules or components.
2.5  CMS Manages Approved Variation, Not Structural Invention
The CMS may manage page instances and approved page-level or module-level variation, but may not invent new structural behavior, new buildable module categories, or new composition rules.
2.6  Reusable Before Bespoke
Where a realization need can be satisfied through an approved reusable module or approved reusable component without distortion, that option must be preferred over bespoke local creation.
2.7  Constrained Composition Is the Default
The default authoring and realization posture is constrained composition, not open composition.
2.8  Structural Clarity Over Local Convenience
Modules, components, and page composition rules must remain clear and governable even where local shortcuts would seem faster.
3.  Buildable Modules
3.1  Buildable Module Meaning
A buildable module is a larger self-contained realizable website unit used to deliver a meaningful website capability or page-level function within the structural architecture.

A buildable module:
•	has a defined purpose
•	has defined inputs and outputs
•	may consume governed content and governed configuration
•	may use reusable components
•	may participate in governed page composition
•	does not redefine the structural architecture

A buildable module is not:
•	a logical module from the Website Solution Architecture Standard
•	a reusable UI component
•	a free-form section invented locally
•	a page type
•	a whole page

It is a realizable functional unit used within governed page composition.
3.2  Buildable Module Categories
The buildable module model contains three governed categories:
•	Site-frame modules — buildable modules that provide site-wide or cross-page realized structure and are used across multiple page types
•	Page-body modules — buildable modules that provide page-facing realized functional content or interaction within one or more page types
•	Support modules — non-visible or supporting realization units required to complete governed page behavior where such responsibility is not already sufficiently covered by page composition or reusable components

All buildable modules must be classified into one of these three categories.
3.3  Canonical Buildable Modules
The closed starting set of canonical buildable modules is:

Site-frame modules:
•	Primary Navigation Module
•	Header Identity Module
•	Footer Module

Page-body modules:
•	Homepage Hero Module
•	Section Landing Module
•	Listing Module
•	Detail Module
•	Rich Content Section Module
•	Featured Content Module
•	Call-to-Action Module
•	Inquiry Module
•	FAQ Module
•	Proof and Testimonial Module

Support modules:
•	Metadata Output Module
•	Redirect and Canonical Handling Module, where required by scope
3.4  Buildable Module Definition Requirements
Every buildable module defined or instantiated under this standard must specify:
•	purpose
•	primary functional responsibility
•	required inputs
•	optional inputs
•	governed content consumed
•	governed configuration consumed
•	outputs or rendered responsibilities
•	reusable components it may use
•	dependencies on other approved services or modules where allowed
•	what it must not do
•	which logical module or logical modules from the Website Solution Architecture Standard it primarily realizes
3.5  Buildable Module Ownership
Each buildable module must own one primary functional realization responsibility.

It must not absorb unrelated page-level, configuration-level, or architecture-level responsibilities merely because doing so is locally convenient.
3.6  Buildable Module Extension
A new buildable module may be introduced only when:
•	the need cannot be satisfied by an existing buildable module without distortion
•	the need cannot be satisfied by page composition using existing buildable modules and reusable components
•	the new module is added through governed extension
4.  Reusable Components
4.1  Reusable Component Meaning
A reusable component is a smaller reusable building part that may be used across multiple buildable modules and contexts.

A reusable component:
•	performs a smaller rendering or interaction job
•	is composable within approved contexts
•	does not become a substitute for a buildable module
•	does not assume ownership of page-level concerns unless explicitly delegated

A reusable component is not:
•	a logical module
•	a buildable module
•	a page type
•	a page composition rule

It is a reusable building part.
4.2  Canonical Reusable Components
The closed starting set of canonical reusable components is:
•	Button
•	Link Group
•	Section Header
•	Rich Text Block
•	Media Block
•	Card
•	Card Grid
•	Badge or Label
•	Breadcrumb
•	Form Field
•	Field Group
•	Accordion Item
•	Quote Block
•	CTA Strip
•	Pagination Control
•	Tag List
4.3  Reusable Component Definition Requirements
Every reusable component defined or instantiated under this standard must specify:
•	purpose
•	contexts in which it may be used
•	contexts in which it must not be used as a substitute for a module
•	inputs
•	outputs or rendered responsibility
•	accessibility expectations where relevant
•	interaction expectations where relevant
•	configuration consumed where relevant
•	composability constraints
4.4  Anti-Substitution Rule
A reusable component must not be used to substitute for a buildable module merely because the module would require more discipline or more explicit composition.
4.5  Component Ownership
A reusable component must not silently assume page-level ownership, module-level ownership, or architectural ownership unless explicitly delegated by a governed rule.
4.6  Module and Component Relationship Rules
Buildable modules may use reusable components.

Reusable components do not replace buildable modules.

A reusable component may be shared across multiple buildable modules only where its meaning remains consistent across those contexts.

A buildable module may specialize component usage within approved bounds, but may not redefine the component into a new implicit component or new implicit module without governed extension.
5.  Page Model
5.1  Page Type
A page type is a governed structural pattern that defines:
•	what a page is for
•	which buildable modules are allowed, required, optional, prohibited, or repeatable
•	what page-level concerns apply
•	what CMS-managed variation is allowed

For each page type, this standard or its governed extension must define:
•	page purpose
•	mandatory modules
•	optional modules
•	prohibited modules
•	repeatable modules
•	mutually exclusive modules, if any
•	page-level concerns
•	allowed CMS-managed variation
•	page regions, if page regions are used
5.2  Canonical Page Types
The closed starting set of canonical page types is:
•	Home
•	Section Landing
•	Listing
•	Detail
•	Contact
•	Static Information
5.2A  Page Type Versus Buildable Module Rule
A page type defines the class of page and the composition rules that govern it. A buildable module defines a realizable functional unit that may be used within one or more page types. A page type is not a module, and a module is not a page type, even where their names are related. A page type may require one or more specific buildable modules as part of its governed composition pattern.
5.3  Page Instance
A page instance is a specific managed page that conforms to a page type.

A page instance defines:
•	content bindings
•	metadata and page-specific settings
•	lifecycle state
•	approved selected modules within page-type rules
•	approved page-level variation within governed bounds
5.4  Page Composition
Page composition is the governed assembly of a page instance from approved buildable modules and reusable components according to page-type rules.
5.5  Realization Classification Rules
Every realized concern in the governed website system must be classified as one of the following:
•	buildable module
•	reusable component
•	page type concern
•	page instance concern
•	page composition concern
•	CMS-managed variation concern

If the concern is a larger self-contained functional website unit that delivers a meaningful capability within page composition, classify it as a buildable module.

If the concern is a smaller reusable building part that supports one or more buildable modules across contexts, classify it as a reusable component.

If the concern defines what classes of pages exist and what module composition rules apply to them, classify it as a page type concern.

If the concern defines page-specific bindings, metadata, settings, or lifecycle for one realized page, classify it as a page instance concern.

If the concern defines how approved modules are assembled, ordered, regioned, or coordinated on a page, classify it as a page composition concern.

If the concern defines what editors may vary within governed bounds, classify it as a CMS-managed variation concern.

A concern must not be classified as a reusable component merely because doing so is easier than defining a proper buildable module.

A concern must not be classified as a buildable module merely because it is visually prominent if its real responsibility is page type, page composition, or CMS-managed variation.
6.  Page Composition Rules
6.1  Page Composition Ownership
A page is assembled by the governed page composition mechanism.

Buildable modules do not assemble the page themselves.
6.2  Page-Level Ownership
Page-level concerns are owned by the page composition model unless explicitly delegated to a buildable module by the page type definition.

A buildable module must not assume ownership of a page-level concern unless that delegation is explicit.
6.3  Module Ownership Limit
A buildable module may be visually prominent or functionally central on a page, but it does not thereby own the page structure.

Page structure, page-level sequencing, page-level accessibility hierarchy, and page-level orchestration remain owned by the page composition model unless explicitly delegated by the page type definition.
6.4  Page Regions
A page type may define governed page regions where composition control requires regional placement.

When page regions are defined, buildable modules must be placed only within those approved regions and according to the page composition rules for that page type.
6.5  Ordering
A page type must define the ordering logic for its modules wherever order is structurally significant.

Modules must not be reordered in a way that violates:
•	mandatory precedence
•	required explanatory sequence
•	required interaction sequence
•	required page-level accessibility structure
6.6  Repeatability
Only modules explicitly marked repeatable for a page type may appear multiple times within one page composition.
6.7  Prohibitions and Mutual Exclusivity
A prohibited module for a page type must not appear on a page instance of that type.

Where modules are declared mutually exclusive for a page type, the page composition model must enforce that constraint.
