6.9  Module Integration Contracts
Every buildable module must expose a defined integration contract.

Each integration contract must define:
•	required inputs
•	optional inputs
•	required content bindings
•	optional content bindings
•	required configuration bindings
•	page context required, if any
•	outputs or rendered responsibility
•	reusable components used
•	assumptions permitted about neighboring modules
•	assumptions prohibited about neighboring modules
•	page-level services or facilities it may use
•	page-level concerns it is explicitly delegated, if any

A buildable module must not depend on hidden local assumptions about page composition, neighboring modules, or CMS data shape outside its declared contract.
7.  CMS Management Rules
7.1  What the CMS May Manage
The CMS may manage page instances and approved page-level or module-level variation within governed bounds.

Where explicitly permitted by the relevant page type and module contract, the CMS may manage:
•	page instances
•	approved module selection within allowed sets
•	approved module ordering where ordering is flexible
•	approved featured-content selection
•	page metadata
•	lifecycle state
•	page-specific textual or media content
•	approved page-specific settings
7.2  What the CMS May Not Manage
The CMS may not:
•	invent new buildable module categories
•	invent new reusable component categories
•	redefine page types
•	bypass page composition rules
•	violate dependency or ownership rules
•	redefine structural responsibilities
•	bypass governed configuration pathways
7.3  Default Authoring Posture
The default authoring posture is constrained composition.

Editors may vary only those aspects explicitly declared as CMS-manageable for the relevant page type, page instance, or buildable module.

Open composition is not the default behavior.
8.  Structural Conformity, Extension, and Mapping
8.1  Relationship to the Website Solution Architecture Standard
Every buildable module must map to one or more logical modules from the Website Solution Architecture Standard.

This document must realize the structural system defined by the Website Solution Architecture Standard and must not redefine the meaning of its logical modules.

Page composition rules, module contracts, and CMS page-management rules must preserve:
•	logical module boundaries
•	dependency rules
•	orthogonality rules
•	architecture invariants
8.2  Extension Rules
This standard must support approved growth without local invention.

A new buildable module may be introduced only through governed extension.

A new reusable component may be introduced only when:
•	an existing reusable component cannot serve the need without distortion
•	the need does not properly belong to an existing buildable module
•	the new reusable component is added through governed extension

A new page type may be introduced only through governed extension.

A new page composition rule or new page-level orchestration rule may be introduced only through governed extension.
8.3  Technology Boundary and Mapping Readiness
This document must remain independent of specific implementation technologies.

The buildable modules, reusable components, page types, and page composition rules must be defined clearly enough that the Technical Build Profile can map them to the chosen stack through straightforward translation rather than reinterpretation.
9.  Site-Specific Realization and Conformance
9.1  Required Contents of Site-Specific Realization Profiles
Every site-specific realization profile derived from this standard must include:
•	scope and relationship to upstream artifacts
•	selected canonical buildable modules
•	selected canonical reusable components
•	selected page types
•	page-type-specific module composition
•	module contracts used
•	CMS-managed versus fixed choices
•	deviations or extensions, if any
•	conformance checks
9.2  Conformance Model
Conformance exists to ensure that realized website pages and modules remain within the governed buildable system and continue to conform to the Website Solution Architecture Standard.

At minimum, assess:
•	were only approved buildable modules used
•	were reusable components used within approved bounds
•	were page types respected
•	were prohibited modules excluded
•	were mandatory modules included
•	were page composition rules followed
•	was page composition centrally owned
•	were module contracts respected
•	did CMS-managed variation remain within approved bounds
•	did realization preserve the structural rules defined upstream

Conformance to this standard must be assessed whenever:
•	a new site-specific realization profile is created
•	a materially revised realization profile is proposed
•	a new buildable module, reusable component, page type, or composition rule is proposed

Conformance assessment must be performed by the document owner or delegated governance owner for website realization and page composition.

A realized page, module, component usage pattern, or CMS-managed behavior that materially violates this standard's buildable module model, component model, page model, composition rules, CMS rules, or upstream structural constraints must not be treated as accepted until the non-conformance is resolved or explicitly authorized as a governed exception.
9.3  Final Governing Statements
This document defines the buildable realization system for website solutions governed under the Website Solution System Framework.

This document is authoritative within its declared scope for:
•	buildable modules
•	reusable components
•	page model
•	page composition
•	CMS-managed realization boundaries
